  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a concept in response to organized crime activities\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities like drug trafficking\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major anti-money laundering legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Created framework for tracking suspicious financial transactions\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against Illicit Drug Trafficking\n- Established international standards for combating money laundering\n- Encouraged global cooperation in financial crime prevention\n\n4. Major Legislation:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Defined money laundering as a federal criminal offense\n- Established comprehensive legal framework for prosecution\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards and recommendations\n- Promotes global policy development and implementation\n\n6. Modern Era:\n- Expanded scope beyond drug trafficking\n- Includes terrorism financing, tax evasion, and other financial crimes\n- Increasingly sophisticated regulatory compliance requirements\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal methods.",
